The symmetric difference of two sets A and B, denoted as A △ B, is the set of elements which are in either A or B, but not in their intersection. In other words, it is the union of the sets minus their intersection: A △ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B).

First, let's find A △ B:
A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4}
A ∩ B = {2, 3}
A △ B = {1, 4}

Now, let's find (A △ B) △ C:
(A △ B) ∪ C = {1, 3, 4, 5}
(A △ B) ∩ C = {3, 4}
(A △ B) △ C = {1, 5}

So, the symmetric difference (A △ B) △ C is the set {1, 5}.
